text: If you are using the latest version of Django(above 1.81),  you might be getting the datetime issue in your console for setting a default in the DateField using datetime.now(). Here's a fix:   IMPORT THIS    from django.utils import timezone CHANGE THIS   only_date_field = models.DateField('Date Posted', default = datetime.now()) TO THIS   only_date_field = models.DateField('Completion Date', default = timezone.now)

author: @AliKHYAR
text: makemigration will create the migration. A migration basically tells your database how it's being changed(i.e new column added, new table, dropped tables etc.).   migrate is what pushes your changes to your database. It will run all the migrations created(or the ones that haven't been pushed yet).

author: @egenethebest9107
text: I don't quite like Django's approach to managing data. I am a Java EE developer and the fact that Django generates the database for you seems wrong. In my opinion you should take a bottom to top development approach. As in first design your database (making sure your data is in 3NF), and only then create the data model in your code (be it Java, Python, JavaScript or anything). If you chose you can then abstract the data model even further, however, first designing the data model, then generating the database seems extremely inefficient especially if you want to scale later on.
